The genealogy of Jesus Christ.
The book of the generation of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham.
Abraham was the father of Isaac. And Isaac was the father of Jacob. And Jacob was the father of Judah and his brothers.
And Judas begot Pharez and Zarah of Tamar. And Pharez begot Hezron. And Hezron begot Aram.
And Aram begat Amminadab. And Amminadab begat Nahshon. And Nahshon begat Salmon.
And Salmon begat Boaz of Rahab. And Boaz begat Obed of Ruth. And Obed begat Jesse.
And Jesse begat David the king. And David the king begat Solomon of her that had been the wife of Uriah.
Solomon was the son of Rehoboam. Rehoboam was the son of Abia. Abia was the son of Asa.
Asa was the son of Jehoshaphat. And Jehoshaphat was the father of Joram. And Joram was the father of Uzziah.
Uzziah the father of Jotham, Jotham the father of Ahaz, Ahaz the father of Hezekiah.
Hezekiah the son of Ahaz, the son of Jotham, the son of Uzziah, the son of Jotham, the son of Ahaz, the son of Jotham.
Josiah became the father of Jehoiachin and his brothers at the time of the Babylonian exile.
And after the Babylonian exile, Jeconiah fathered Shealtiel. And Shealtiel fathered Zerubbabel.
And Zerubbabel was born to Abiud; and Abiud was born to Eliakim; and Eliakim was born to Azor;
Azur the son of Sadok, Sadok the son of Achim, Achim the son of Elioud.
And Eliakim was the father of Eliezer. And Eliezer was the father of Mattan. And Mattan was the father of Jacob.
And Jacob begot Joseph, the husband of Mary, from whom was born Jesus, who is called the Christ.
All generations from Abraham to David are fourteen generations, and from David to the Babylonian exile are fourteen generations, and from the Babylonian exile to the Messiah are fourteen generations. The birth of Jesus Christ.
Now the birth of Jesus Christ was as follows: When His mother Mary was engaged to Joseph, before they came together, she was found with child from the Holy Spirit.
Joseph, her husband, being a righteous man, did not wish to expose her publicly. He intended to divorce her privately.
But while he was thinking about these things, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream, saying, "Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary your wife, for that which is conceived in her is of the Holy Spirit."
She will give birth to a son, and you are to give him the name Jesus, because he will save his people from their sins."
And all this took place to fulfill what the Lord had said through the prophet:
"Behold, the virgin shall be with child and shall bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel," which, being interpreted, means "God with us."
When Joseph woke up from sleep, he did as the angel of the Lord had commanded him, and he took his wife.
And he did not know her until she gave birth to her firstborn son. And he called his name Jesus.
Visit of the Magi
And when Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea, in the days of Herod the king, behold, there came wise men from the east to Jerusalem.
saying, "Where is he who was born king of the Jews? For we have seen his star in the east and have come to worship him."
When Herod the king heard this, he was disturbed, and all Jerusalem with him.
So he gathered all the chief priests and the writers of the people, and he asked them, "Where is Christ to be born?"
They said to him, "In Bethlehem of Judea; for it is written by the prophet,
And you, Bethlehem, land of Judah, are by no means least among the leaders of Judah; for out of you will come a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel.'
Then Herod secretly called the Magi and inquired of them carefully the time when the star appeared.
Then he sent them to Bethlehem and said, "Go and search carefully for the young child. And when you have found him, report to me, so that I may also come and worship him."
When they heard from the king, they departed. And behold, the star which they had seen in the east went before them until it came and stood over where the young child was.
When they saw the star, they rejoiced exceedingly with great joy.
And they came to the house and saw the child with Mary his mother. And they fell down and worshipped him. Then they opened their treasures and presented him with gifts: gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
Then, when an angel appeared to them in a dream and told them, "Do not go back to Herod," they left by another road to their own region, the flight to Egypt.
And after they departed, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream, saying, "Arise, and take the young child and his mother, and flee into Egypt, and be there until I bring you word. For Herod the tetrarch is seeking the young child to destroy him."
And when he rose up, he took the child and his mother by night and departed for Egypt.
And he remained there until the death of Herod. So that what was spoken by the Lord through the prophet might be fulfilled, saying: "Out of Egypt I have called my son."
When Herod saw that the Magi had mocked him, he became very angry. He sent and killed all the young boys in Bethlehem and in all its surrounding areas, from two years old and under, according to the time he had carefully inquired about from the Magi.
Then was fulfilled that which was spoken by Jeremy the prophet, saying:
A voice was heard in Ramah, lamentation and great weeping and mourning. Rachel weeping for her children and refusing to be comforted, because they are no more. Return to Nazareth.
When Herod died, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt,
Saying, "Rise and take the boy and his mother and go to the land of Israel, because those who were seeking the boy's life have died."
He rose, took the boy and his mother, and came to the land of Israel.
But when he heard that Herod Antipas was ruling over the region of Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. And after he was warned in a dream, he departed to the regions of Galilee.
And he came and dwelt in a city called Nazareth, that what was spoken by the prophets might be fulfilled: "He shall be called a Nazarene."
John the Baptist paves the way.
And in those days John the Baptist came, preaching in the wilderness of Judea, saying:
Saying, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand."
For this is he that was spoken of by the prophet Isaiah, saying: "The voice of one crying in the wilderness: 'Prepare the way of the Lord. Make his paths straight.'"
And John the Baptist was clothed with camel's hair, and around his hips was a leather belt. And his food was locusts and wild honey.
Then all Jerusalem and all Judea and all the region around the Jordan went out to him.
And they were baptized by him in the River Jordan, confessing their sins.
When he saw many of the Pharisees and Sadducees coming to his baptism, he said to them, "You brood of vipers, who warned you to flee from the coming wrath?
Therefore, bear fruit worthy of repentance.
And do not think to say to yourselves, 'We have Abraham as our father.' For I say to you, God is able from these stones to raise up children to Abraham.
And now the axe is laid to the root of the trees; therefore every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
I baptize you with water for repentance, but he who comes after me is mightier than I, whose sandals I am not worthy to carry. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire.
The one who has a shovel in his hand will clear his threshing floor and gather his wheat into the barn. But the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire.» The Baptism of Jesus Christ
Then Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan to John, to be baptized by him.
But John tried to prevent him, saying, "I need to be baptized by you, and you come to me!"
Jesus answered and said to him, "Allow it to be so now, for thus it is fitting for us to fulfill all righteousness." Then he allowed him.
When Jesus was baptized, he immediately went up out of the water, and behold, the heavens were opened to him, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and coming to him.
And a voice from the heavens said, "This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased."
Jesus faces temptation.
Then Jesus was led up by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil.
After fasting for forty days and forty nights, he was finally hungry.
Then the tempter came and said to him, "If you are the Son of God, command that these stones become bread."
He answered and said, "It is written: 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds from the mouth of God.'"
Then the devil took him to the holy city, and he stood him on a pinnacle of the temple,
And he said to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written: 'He will command his angels concerning you, and they will lift you up in their hands, so that you will not strike your foot against a stone.' "
Jesus said to him, "It is written again: 'Do not test the Lord your God.'"
Then the devil took him to a very high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
And he said to him, "I will give you all these, if you will fall down and worship me."
Then Jesus said to him, "Go away, Satan! For it is written: 'You shall worship the Lord your God, and him alone shall you serve.'"
Then Satan left him, and behold, angels came and began to minister to him. The Beginning of His Ministry in Galilee
And when Jesus heard that John had been delivered up, he withdrew to Galilee.
And leaving Nazareth, he came and lived in Capernaum, which is by the sea, in the region of Zebulun and Naphthali.
In order that what was spoken through Isaiah the prophet, who said:
"The land of Zebulun, and the land of Naphtali, by the way of the sea, through the Jordan, Galilee of the nations."
The people who dwell in the land of deep darkness have seen a great light; and for those who sit in the region and shadow of death, upon them a light has dawned.
From that time Jesus began to preach, saying, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand." The Calling of the First Disciples
As Jesus was walking by the Sea of Galilee, he saw two brothers, Simon (the one who is called Peter) and his brother Andrew, casting a net into the sea, for they were fishermen.
And he said to them, "Come after me, and I will make you fishers of men."
For a time, they left the nets and followed him.
Then He passed from there and saw another two brothers: James the son of Zebedee, and John his brother, in the boat with Zebedee their father, mending their nets; so He called them.
Immediately they left the boat, and their father, and followed him. Jesus teaches and heals the sick.
And Jesus was going throughout all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, and preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every weakness among the people.
And his fame spread throughout Syria. And all the sick, those afflicted with various diseases and pains, and the insane, those possessed and paralyzed, were brought to him, and he healed them.
Great multitudes from Galilee, Decapolis, Jerusalem, Judea, and beyond the Jordan followed him.
The Sermon on the Mount - The Beatitudes
And when he saw the multitudes, he went up into a mountain: and when he was set, his disciples came unto him.
He opened His mouth and taught them, saying:
Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are those who mourn, for they will be comforted.
Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled.
Blessed are the merciful, for they will be shown mercy.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they will be called children of God.
Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness' sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are you when they revile you and persecute you, and say all manner of evil against you falsely, for my sake.
Rejoice and be glad, because your reward is great in heaven; for in the same way they persecuted the prophets who were before you. Salt of the earth and light of the world.
You are the salt of the earth; but if the salt loses its flavor, how can it be made salty again? It is no longer good for anything, except to be thrown out and trampled under people's feet.
You are the light of the world. No one lights a lamp and puts it under a basket, but rather puts it on a lampstand, so that those who come in may see the light.
And they do not light a lamp and put it under a measuring basket, but rather on the lampstand, so that it may give light to all who are in the house.
Let your light shine before men, that they may see your good works and glorify your Father who is in heaven. Fulfillment of the Law.
Do not suppose that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish but to complete.
For truly I say to you: until heaven and earth pass away, not even one letter or one stroke of a letter will pass away from the Law until all is accomplished.
For whoever keeps the whole law and yet stumbles in one point, he has become accountable for all of it. But the person who does not know the law of the trespasses, but does the forbidden things, will be subject to the judgment. The one who teaches his neighbor the law will be counted as a great one in the kingdom of heaven. But the one who does the law and teaches it will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
For I tell you: Unless your righteousness surpasses that of the scribes and Pharisees, you will not enter the kingdom of heaven. Wrath
You have heard that it was said to the people long ago, 'You shall not murder; and anyone who murders will be subject to judgment.'
But I say to you: Everyone who is angry with his brother shall be guilty before the court; and whoever says to his brother, 'You good-for-nothing,' shall be guilty enough to go to the Sanhedrin; and whoever says, 'You fool,' shall be guilty enough to go into the everlasting fire.
If you present your offering at the altar and there remember that your brother has something against you,
Therefore, leave your offering there before the altar, and first go and be reconciled to your brother; and then come and offer your gift.
Be quick to satisfy your opponent as long as you are both on the road, lest your opponent hand you over to the judge, and the judge hand you over to the policeman, and you be thrown into prison.
Truly I tell you: Do not leave there until you have paid the last penny! Adultery.
You have heard that it was said to the people long ago, 'You shall not commit adultery.'
But I say to you: whoever looks at a woman to desire her has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
If your right eye causes you to stumble, gouge it out and throw it away. It is better for you to lose one of your members than for your whole body to be thrown into hell.
And if your right hand causes you to stumble, cut it off and throw it away from you, because it is better for you to lose one of your members than for your whole body to be thrown into hell. Divorce.
And it was said: Whoever divorces his wife, let him give her a written bill of divorce.
But I say to you: whoever divorces his wife, unless it is for sexual immorality, makes her commit adultery; and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. The End.
You have also heard that it was said to the people long ago, 'You shall not break an oath, but shall fulfill to the Lord the vows you make to Him.'
And I say to you, do not swear at all, not by heaven, for it is the throne of God,
Neither by the earth, for it is his footstool; nor by Jerusalem, for it is the city of the great King.
And do not swear by your head, for you cannot make even one hair white or black.
Let your statement be: 'Yes, yes' or 'No, no.' What is more than this comes from the evil one. Vengeance.
You have heard that it was said, 'An eye for an eye, and a tooth for a tooth.'
But I say to you, Do not resist an evildoer. But whoever slaps you on your right cheek, turn to him the other cheek also.
And whoever wants to sue you and take your tunic, let him have the cloak as well.
If anyone forces you to go one mile, go with them two miles.
He who asks of you, give to him; and he who wishes to borrow from you, do not turn away from him. Love your enemies.
You have heard that it was said, 'You shall love your neighbor and hate your enemy.'
And I say to you: Love your enemies. Bless those who curse you. Do good to those who hate you, and pray for those who mistreat you and persecute you.
So that you may be the children of your Father who is in heaven; for He causes His sun to rise on the evil and the good, and sends rain on the just and the unjust.
For if you love those who love you, what reward do you have? Do not even the tax collectors do the same?
If you greet only your brothers, what more are you doing than others? Do not even the tax collectors do the same?
Be perfect, therefore, as your heavenly Father is perfect.
Charity
Be careful not to do your acts of righteousness before people, so that they may see you. Otherwise, you will have no reward from your Father in heaven.
Therefore, when you make a charitable contribution, do not sound a trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, so that they may be praised by men. Truly, I say to you, they have received their reward!
And when you make a gift, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing,
In order for your charity to be in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Prayer
And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, for they love to pray standing in the synagogues and at the street corners, so that they may be seen by others. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full!
And when you pray, go into your room and shut the door and pray to your Father who is in secret; and your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly.
And when you pray, do not heap up empty phrases like the Gentiles, for they suppose that they will be heard for their many words.
Do not be like them. For your Father knows what you need before you ask Him.
Pray then like this: Our Father who art in heaven, Hallowed be thy name.
Let your kingdom come. Let your will be done, as in heaven, so on earth.
Give us this day our daily bread.
And forgive us our sins as we also forgive those who sin against us.
And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil. For Yours is the kingdom, and the power, and the glory, forever. Amen.
For if you forgive men their trespasses, your heavenly Father will also forgive you.
And if you do not forgive people their wrongs, your Father will not forgive your wrongs either. Fasting.
And when you fast, do not look somber like the hypocrites, for they disfigure their faces to show others that they are fasting. I tell you the truth, they have received their reward.
And when you fast, anoint your head and wash your face,
So that you may not appear to people as fasting, but rather for your Father who is in secret. For your Father who sees in secret will reward you openly. Treasures in heaven.
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.
Instead, lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust destroys, and where thieves do not break in or steal.
For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.
The lamp of the body is the eye. If therefore your eye is simple, your whole body will be full of light.
And if your eye is evil, your whole body will be full of darkness. And if the light within you is darkness, how great is that darkness!
No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate the one and love the other, or he will be devoted to the one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and wealth. God takes care of us.
Therefore I tell you, do not be worried about your life, what you will eat and what you will drink, nor about your body, what you will wear. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothing?
Look at the birds of the sky: they do not sow nor do they reap, nor do they gather into barns; yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not much better than they?
Who among you, if he is concerned, will be able to add to his height one cubit?
And why do you worry about clothing? Consider the lilies of the field, how they grow! They do not toil, nor do they spin.
But I tell you: Not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of these.
If the grass of the field, which is here today and thrown into the oven tomorrow, is clothed by God in this way, isn't it much more certain that He will clothe you, you of little faith?
Therefore do not worry, saying, 'What will we eat?' or 'What will we drink?' or 'What will we wear?'
For the Gentiles seek after all these things: for your heavenly Father knoweth that ye have need of all these things.
Seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.
Therefore do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself. Sufficient for the day is its own evil.
Condemning others.
Do not judge, and you will not be judged.
For with the judgment you pronounce you will be judged, and with the measure you use it will be measured to you.
And why do you look at the speck of dust that is in your brother's eye, but you do not notice the wooden beam that is in your own eye?
Or how will you say to your brother, 'Let me remove the splinter from your eye,' when you have a wooden beam in your own eye?
Hypocrite, first take the beam out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly to take the splinter out of your brother's eye!
Do not give what is holy to dogs, and do not throw your pearls before swine, lest they trample them under their feet and turn and tear you to pieces. Ask, seek, knock
Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you.
For everyone who asks receives, and the one who seeks finds, and the one who knocks will have the door opened for him.
Or what father among you, if his son asks him for a piece of bread, will give him a stone?
If he asks him for a fish, will he give him a snake?
If, while you are evil, you know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in heaven give good things to those who ask him!
For whatever you want people to do for you, do the same for them; for this is the Law and the Prophets. The narrow gate.
"Enter through the narrow gate, for the gate is wide and the road is easy that leads to destruction, and many are those who enter through it!"
The gate is narrow and the way is hard that leads to life, and few are those who find it! The tree and its fruit.
Beware of false prophets, who come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly are ravenous wolves!
You will recognize them by their fruits. Do people gather grapes from thornbushes or figs from thistles?
Thus every good tree bears good fruit, but a bad tree bears bad fruit.
No good tree can produce bad fruit, nor can a bad tree produce good fruit.
Every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire.
You will recognize them by their fruit.
Not everyone who says to me, 'Lord, Lord,' will enter the kingdom of heaven. For the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven will enter.
Many will say to me on that day: Lord, Lord! Is not your name by which we prophesied, and by which we cast out demons, and by which we did many mighty works?
Therefore, I will openly declare to them: 'I never knew you! Go away from me, you evil-doers!' The wise builders and the foolish builders.
Everyone who hears these words of mine and acts on them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock.
Rain fell, rivers came, winds blew, and it fell upon that house, but it did not fall, because it was founded upon the rock.
And everyone who hears these words of mine and does not act upon them will be like a foolish man who built his house on sand.
And the rain fell, and the rivers came, and the winds blew, and they struck that house, and it fell, and great was its fall!».
When Jesus completed these sayings, the crowds were amazed at his teaching.
For he taught them as one who had authority, and not as the scribes.
Healing of a Leper
And when he came down from the mountain, great crowds followed him.
And behold, a leper came and prostrated himself before him, saying, "Lord, if you are willing, you can make me clean."
Jesus reached out his hand and touched him, saying, "I want to. Be clean!" And immediately his leprosy was cleansed.
Jesus said to him, "Look, do not say this to anyone. But go, show yourself to the priest, and offer the sacrifice that Moses commanded, as a testimony to them." The Faith of the Centurion
And when Jesus entered Capernaum, a centurion came to him, appealing to him.
And he says, "Lord, my servant lies at home paralyzed and severely tormented."
Jesus said to him, "I will come and heal him."
The centurion answered and said, "Master, I am not worthy that you should enter under my roof, but just say the word and my servant will be healed."
For also I am a man under authority, having soldiers under me; and I say to one, Go! and he goes; and to another, Come! and he comes; and to my servant, Do this! and he does it."
When Jesus heard this, he was amazed and said to those who followed him, "I tell you the truth: I have not found such great faith, even in Israel!
And I say to you, that many will come from the east and the west, and will recline with Abraham and Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of the heavens.
As for the sons of the kingdom, they will be cast into the outer darkness. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth."
Then Jesus said to the centurion, "Go, and as you believed, so let it be done for you." And his servant was healed that very hour. Healing of Peter's Mother-in-law and Others
And when Jesus came to Peter's house, he saw his mother-in-law lying down, sick with a fever.
He touched her hand, and the fever left her. She rose and served them.
And when evening came, they brought to Him many who were possessed by demons; and He cast out the spirits by a word, and He healed all who were sick.
In order for what was said by Isaiah the prophet to be fulfilled, the one who said, "He took our infirmities and carried our diseases," bore the cost of discipleship.
And when Jesus saw the great multitudes around Him, He commanded to go to the other side.
Then a scribe came forward and said to him, "Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go."
Jesus said to him, "Foxes have dens and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head."
And another of his disciples said to him, "Lord, permit me first to go and bury my father."
Jesus said to him, "Follow me, and let the dead bury their own dead." The Calming of the Storm
And when he entered the boat, his disciples followed him.
And a great tempest arose on the sea, so that the waves beat into the boat, and it was already filled. But he was sleeping.
His disciples came to Him and awoke Him, saying, "Lord, save us! We are perishing!"
He said to them, "Why are you afraid, O little faith?" Then He rose and rebuked the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm.
And the people were astonished, saying, "What kind of man is this? Even the winds and the sea obey him!" He cast out demons.
And when He came to the other side, to the region of the Gadarenes, two demoniacs met Him coming out of the tombs. They were so fierce that no one could pass by that road.
And behold, they cried out, saying, "What have you to do with us, Jesus, Son of God? Have you come here before the time to torment us?"
And a little way from them a large herd of pigs was feeding.
So the demons begged him, saying, "If you cast us out, permit us to go into the herd of pigs."
And He said to them, "Go." And they came out and went to the herd of pigs; and behold, the entire herd of pigs was rushing down the steep bank into the sea, and they died in the water.
The shepherds fled and went to the city, and reported everything, and about the matter of the two possessed.
And behold, the whole city went out to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they begged that he would depart from their borders.
Healing of a Paralytic
So he entered the boat, crossed over, and came to his own city.
And behold, a paralytic was being carried to Him, laying on a bed. When Jesus saw their faith, He said to the paralytic, "Take courage, son; your sins are forgiven."
And behold, scribes who said within themselves, "This man blasphemes!"
Jesus knew their thoughts, so he said, "Why do you think evil in your hearts?"
Which is easier, to say, Your sins are forgiven, or to say, Rise up and walk?
But so that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins. Then He said to the paralytic, "Get up, pick up your bed and go to your house."
So he got up and went to his house.
When the crowds saw it, they were amazed and glorified God who had given such authority to people. The Calling of Matthew.
As Jesus was passing by there, he saw a man sitting at the tax office, his name was Matthew. And he said to him, "Follow me." And he rose and followed him.
And as he reclined at the table in the house, behold, tax collectors and many sinners came and reclined with Jesus and his disciples.
When the Pharisees saw this, they said to his disciples, "Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?"
When Jesus heard this, he said to them, "It is not those who are well who need a physician, but those who are ill."
Go then, and learn what this is: I desire mercy and not sacrifice, for I did not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance.» The question about fasting.
Then the disciples of John came to him, saying, "Why do we and the Pharisees fast often, but your disciples do not fast?"
Jesus said to them, "Can the wedding guests mourn as long as the bridegroom is with them? But the days will come when the bridegroom is taken away from them; then they will fast.
No one sews a patch of new cloth on an old garment, because the new patch will take away from the old garment, making the tear even worse.
And they don't put new wine into old wineskins, lest the wineskins burst, and the wine spills out, and the wineskins are ruined. But they put new wine into new wineskins, and both are preserved." The raising of Jairus' daughter and the healing of the woman with the bloody discharge. (Note: The original Arabic text appears to be a mix of standard Arabic and potentially some dialectal or informal elements, which can sometimes make precise translation slightly more challenging. However, the provided English translation aims to be as accurate and faithful as possible to the original meaning, while maintaining a professional and natural flow in English.)
And while he was speaking to them, behold, a ruler came and knelt before him, saying, "My daughter has just now died; but come and lay your hand on her, and she will live."
Jesus rose up and he, along with his disciples, followed him.
And behold, a woman who had been suffering from a hemorrhage for twelve years came up behind Him and touched the tassel of His robe;
For she said to herself, "If I touch even his clothes, I will be healed."
Jesus turned and saw her, and said, "Take heart, daughter; your faith has made you well." And the woman was well from that hour.
